<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25048m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25048m">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25048m"> 48(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the jambs</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The next stage in the construction of a doorway shows us that those ancient builders inserted a lintel at a certain height and made <mark>the jambs</mark> more perpendicular below and more sloping above; the second sketch (which has been copied from the &lsquo;Gate of Lions&rsquo; at Mycenae) shows further progress. But even there, although the jambs are single stones, they incline, and an effort has been made to preserve the old shape above the lintel, so that its ancient tent-like character may be kept. Our third engraving shows the fully developed and inclined Celtic jamb. <small> J. F. M. Ffrench, <a name="JFPF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JFPF"><cite title="source">Prehistoric Faith and Worship</cite></a> (1912) 121-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14026h" href="c14all.htm#c14026h">VI.C.14:026(h)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
